{"questionId":"17656","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A spaceship is travelling at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>80</mn><mi>c</mi></math>, away from Earth. It launches a probe away from Earth, at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>50</mn><mi>c</mi></math> relative to the spaceship. An observer on the probe measures the length of the probe to be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/aee8bc834cd8310b5a3642fec244d2215725375a.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Explain which of the lengths is the proper length.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span class=\"fontstyle0\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math> / measurement made on the probe </span><span class=\"fontstyle2\">✓<br></span></p>\n<p><span class=\"fontstyle0\">the measurement made by an observer at rest in the frame of the probe </span><span class=\"fontstyle2\">✓</span></p>","meta":{"questionId":"17656","referenceCode":"20N.3.SL.TZ0.4b(ii)","subjectId":"46-dp-physics-last-assessment-2024","title":"Explain which of the lengths is the proper length.","paper":"3","level":"SL","questionNumber":"b(ii)","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Option A: Relativity","Option A: Relativity","Option A: Relativity (Core topics)","A.2 – Lorentz transformations","Option A: Relativity","Option A: Relativity (Core topics)"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}